{#
  submission_readme_template.j2 -- VeriFlow's default submission README.

  Rendered by `veriflow project generate-readme`
  (_readme_render_context() + generate_readme() in veriflow/api.py). To
  customize: copy this file, point `readme_template:` in veriflow.yaml (or
  --template) at your copy, and edit freely -- the context below is
  everything this template (or yours) can reference, from two distinct
  sources kept deliberately separate (see _readme_render_context()'s
  docstring for why):

  From the CURRENT veriflow.yaml (live config, re-read on every call --
  reflects any `veriflow project set` change immediately, even without a
  new `project run`):
    interface_name        -- config.interface's name, or null for a
                             generic project (str | None)
    interface_ports        -- [{"name", "direction", "width"}, ...] for
                             interface_name's profile; [] for a generic
                             project (no interface configured)
    interface_port_descriptions -- {port_name: description}; the profile's
                             own meta.yaml merged with veriflow.yaml's
                             interface.port_descriptions override (the
                             latter wins per port); {} if neither exists
    technology             -- config.technology's name (str)
    description            -- metadata.description, "" if unset
    author                 -- metadata.author, "" if unset
    version                -- metadata.version, "" if unset
    tile_name              -- metadata.name, falling back to top_module
                             (from the LAST RUN, see below) when unset
    repo_owner, repo_name  -- parsed from the GITHUB_REPOSITORY env var
                             ("owner/repo", set automatically by GitHub
                             Actions); both None when that variable isn't
                             set (e.g. generating locally) -- check
                             `{% if repo_owner and repo_name %}` before
                             using them, don't assume they're set

  From the latest PASSING run's results.json (verification facts that
  can't be back-filled from the live config -- what actually ran, not
  what's currently configured; see workflows/project.py::_write_results_json):
    top_module          -- RTL top module name as of that run (str)
    rtl_sources           -- RTL source paths, relative to veriflow.yaml (list[str])
    tb_sources            -- testbench source paths, relative to veriflow.yaml (list[str])
    rtl_hash              -- {filename: sha256_hex} for every RTL source (dict[str, str])
    stages                -- {"connectivity": {...}, "simulation": {...}, "synthesis": {...}};
                             each stage dict has at least "status" (PASS/FAIL/SKIPPED) and "log"
    warnings              -- warning strings collected across all stages (list[str])
    veriflow_version      -- VeriFlow version that produced that run (str)
    timestamp             -- ISO 8601 UTC timestamp of that run (str) -- timestamp[:10]
                             gives just the date (YYYY-MM-DD)
    status                -- that run's overall status -- always "PASS" here,
                             since generate-readme only ever looks at a passing run

  Note the asymmetry this creates by design: if veriflow.yaml's interface/
  technology changed since the last passing run, this README shows the
  *new* interface/technology name and port map, while `stages` still shows
  what that older run actually verified -- run `veriflow project run`
  again to make both agree.
#}
# {{ tile_name }} -- VeriFlow Submission

{# CI badge: only meaningful once this repo is actually pushed to GitHub
   (GITHUB_REPOSITORY is set by GitHub Actions itself). A README generated
   locally, before a first push, would otherwise get a badge pointing at
   a literal "owner/repo" that always 404s -- show a plain HTML comment
   placeholder instead; it's invisible in rendered Markdown but tells
   anyone reading the raw file why there's no badge yet. #}
{% if repo_owner and repo_name %}
![VeriFlow Precheck](https://github.com/{{ repo_owner }}/{{ repo_name }}/actions/workflows/precheck.yml/badge.svg)
{% else %}
<!-- add badge after pushing to GitHub -->
{% endif %}

{# description is optional (metadata.description in veriflow.yaml) --
   skip the blockquote line (and its trailing blank-line separator)
   entirely rather than rendering an empty "> ". The separator lives
   *inside* the if-block so it collapses along with the rest when
   description is unset, instead of leaving a stray blank line behind. #}
{% if description %}
> {{ description }}

{% endif %}
{# author/version are optional (metadata.author/metadata.version) --
   show whichever of the two is actually set, joined by " | " only when
   both are; omit the whole line (and its separator, same reasoning as
   description above) if neither is set. Built from {{ }} expressions
   rather than chained {% if %}/{% endif %} tags on one line -- trim_blocks
   strips the newline right after a block tag, which would otherwise eat
   the blank-line separator below whenever this line ends in {% endif %}. #}
{% if author or version %}
{{ "**Author:** " ~ author if author else "" }}{{ " | " if author and version else "" }}{{ "**Version:** " ~ version if version else "" }}

{% endif %}
